I think being able to distinguish between fast and slow tests and different
kinds of tests is very useful. I can keep fast feedback cycles while
retaining high confidence levels. I can run all the unit tests related
to the area I am working on plus all the fast unit tests for the entire
codebase plus a subset of other kinds of tests that I deem useful (possibly
all the fast integration tests related to the area I am working in).
The &quot;area I am working in&quot; might be a module or package or some other slice
of the codebase - ideally it will be easy for me to select something close
to the relevant tests easily - so aggregating tests over packages or modules
might still be a very useful thing.

I do think distinguishing different kinds of tests is useful. There are
tests which check the environment (perhaps I would call the tableShouldExist
example below an environment test). There are some which might test your
wiring if you are using IOC (you do test drive that don&#39;t you?) and there
are others which test your system&#39;s building blocks (sometimes these are
called integration or system tests - and sometimes they overlap with
acceptance tests). If you are practising Agile then your unit tests are
your code-level documentation and specification and your system tests
are your architectural-level documentation and specification.

Paul.


Cédric Beust ♔ wrote:
&gt; Integration and unit tests are actually not mutually exclusive with fast and
&gt; slow tests.  Here is an example:
&gt; 
&gt; @Test(groups = {&quot;fast&quot;, &quot;unit&quot;})
&gt; public void fullName() {
&gt;   Person p = new Person();
&gt;   p.setFirstName(&quot;Cedric&quot;);
&gt;   p.setLastName(&quot;Beust&quot;);
&gt;   assert &quot;Cedric Beust&quot;.equals(p.getFullName());
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; @Test(groups = {&quot;slow&quot;, &quot;unit&quot;}}
&gt; public void verifyPi() {
&gt;   Pi pi = new Pi();
&gt;   assert pi.getDecimals(10000).equals(EXPECTED_DECIMALS);
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; @Test(groups = {&quot;fast&quot;, &quot;integration&quot;})
&gt; public void tableShouldExist() {
&gt;   // verify that a table exists
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; @Test(groups = {&quot;slow&quot;, &quot;integration&quot;})
&gt; public void insertGraphOfObjects() {
&gt;   // insert a lot of rows in the database
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; With this set up, I have all freedom to run &quot;integration&quot;, &quot;unit&quot;, &quot;fast&quot; or
&gt; &quot;slow&quot; tests.
&gt; 
&gt; This is why trying to represent test groups with packages and class names
&gt; doesn&#39;t scale:  test methods cannot belong to more than one group with that
&gt; approach.
&gt; 
&gt; --
